b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Ultra-low-density exoplanets among least dense ever found"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"James Webb Telescope blocked by mysterious atmospheric smog"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"All atmospheric probing attempts have failed"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The James Webb Space Telescope, humanity's most powerful eye on the cosmos, has met an unexpected adversary: a layer of impenetrable haze surrounding some of the strangest worlds ever discovered. These so-called \"cotton candy\" exoplanets — named for their extraordinarily low density — have resisted every attempt to probe their atmospheres, leaving researchers with more questions than answers. The significance extends beyond mere frustration. These super-puffy worlds challenge our understanding of how planets form and evolve, and the fact that even ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.nasa.gov/mission/webbtelescope/","children":"JWST's sophisticated instruments"}]," cannot penetrate their atmospheric veil suggests we may need entirely new approaches to study them. According to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.space.com","children":"Space.com"}],", the mysterious smog layer has blocked all spectroscopic attempts to determine what these worlds are actually made of. The planets represent some of the least dense objects ever found outside our solar system, yet their composition remains hidden behind this atmospheric curtain. This represents a humbling moment for a mission that has otherwise exceeded expectations at nearly every turn."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/cotton-candy-worlds-defy-jwst-behind-impenetrable-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What remains hidden when our best instruments fall short","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"What remains hidden when our best instruments fall short"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["What makes this particularly frustrating for astronomers is that JWST was specifically designed to characterize exoplanet atmospheres with unprecedented precision. The telescope's near-infrared spectrograph has successfully analyzed dozens of ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/","children":"alien worlds"}],", revealing water vapor, carbon dioxide, and other key molecules in their skies. Yet these cotton candy planets present a unique obstacle — one that early signals suggest may require years to overcome. The haze itself is a scientific puzzle worth solving. Understanding its composition could reveal new chemistry at work in planetary atmospheres, or perhaps indicate processes we haven't yet encountered in our own solar system. For now, researchers must wait. Future observations with different wavelengths or more sophisticated modeling techniques may eventually pierce the veil, though the exact origin of the smog remains uncertain. But this encounter serves as a reminder that even our most advanced technology faces limits when confronting the true diversity of worlds beyond our cosmic neighborhood."]}]]}]
